 of Scottish politics. It does so using a unique source of evidence - representative high quality annual sample surveys of the Scottish public that since 1999 have regularly measured how people in Scotland have reacted to devolution and how they have behaved in elections.Readers will gain an unparalleled insight into the identities, attitudes and electoral behaviour of people in Scotland during the first decade of devolution.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aElectionszScotland. 4aPolitics. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / National.2bisacsh1 aMcCrone, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aMcEwen, Nicola, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOrmston, Rachel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z97831107804680 cprintz978074863899440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780748642151?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780748642151423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780748642151/original  a978-3-11-078046-8  Edinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK